Cicero's return was like a triumphal procession. Not· withstanding his haste to see Rome, such crowds ol friends from all the towns delayed his journey, that he was twenty- four days in passing from Brundisium to Rome. When there, aristocracy and plebeians vied with each other to give him welcome. But his enemies were still lively and strong. “My condition,” wrote he to Atticus, “is lor
